{{For|the villages in Iran|Hamun, Iran|Hamand, Khusf}} {{distinguish|Hamun Lake}} A '''hamun''' (or hamoun) ({{lang-fa|هامون}} ''hāmūn'') refers to seasonal desert lakes or marshlands found on the [[Iranian Plateau]], from [[Iran]] to [[Afghanistan]] and western [[Pakistan]] or [[Balochistan]].<ref name=usgs>{{Cite web | last = Whitney | first = John | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Geology, Water, and Wind in the Lower Helmand Basin | work = | publisher = U.S. Geological Survey | date = 2006 | url = http://pdf.usaid.gov/pdf_docs/PNADH905.pdf | format = | doi = | accessdate = 2010-08-31}}</ref> They form a critical link in the wildlife of the area, aquatic as well as avian and terrestrial.
The better-known hamuns include: *[[Hamun-e Helmand]], Afghanistan and Iran **[[Hamun Lake]], Iran and Afghanistan *[[Hamun-e Jaz Murian]], Iran *Hamun-e [[Mashkel]] or Mashkid, straddling Iran-Pakistan border *Hamun-e Puzak, Afghanistan *Hamun-e Saberi in [[Sistan]], straddling Iran-Afghanistan border *Hamun Zeheh, Goad-i Zereh or [[Godzareh depression]], Afghanistan
